": \"InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7N3O4P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"cytidine 2',3'-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cytidine-2',3'-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH6N3O3P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"diamidophosphoric acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"diamidophosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C9H13N3O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-amino-1-\u03b2-D-ribofuranosyl-1H-pyrimidin-2-one\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cytidine\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_024\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_025\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"aminoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_026\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH5N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_027\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-diaminomaleonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAMN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_028\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_028\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent, H2-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-S phases gives formate as an early C1 fixation product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included as the hydrothermal carbon-fixation entry point required by the network and consistent with Fe-S vent chemistry discussed for greigite/mackinawite and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user-type carbon fixation; hydrothermal supply is upstream only and not used as a free-cytosine production site because cytosine is thermally unstable there (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1990; Navrotsky et al., 2020; Levy & Miller, 1998).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal homologation to formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_028\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type and CO2 hydrogenation regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced C1 species generated at Fe-rich vent interfaces undergo surface-mediated homologation to oxygenated C1/C2 carbonyl compounds.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This connecting reaction is a conservative hydrothermal feedstock step based on magnetite/Fe0-driven FTT-like carbonyl generation and is used to link hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface sugar chemistry; it is speculative in detailed product partitioning but consistent with hydrothermal reduced-carbon synthesis frameworks (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1990; reviewed in the supplied report; FeS hot-spring carbon reduction context in 2024 Nature Communications as summarized in the report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN formation and concentration to glycolonitrile precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_026\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated evaporitic or flow-fed pool with concentration by drying/freezing\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with HCN to give glycolonitrile; mineral surfaces and concentration mechanisms stabilize and channel carbonyl chemistry into nitrile-bearing sugar precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolonitrile is identified in the supplied report as an entry point for sugar synthesis in the cyanosulfidic network; the network uses a connected surface pool receiving hydrothermal formaldehyde and HCN-rich input. UV and concentration mechanisms follow the broader cyanosulfidic scenario (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Sasselov, Grotzinger & Sutherland, 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic homologation of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoredox with sulfide minerals and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV 200-300 nm, H2S as reductant, cyanosulfidic flow chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive homologation of nitrile/carbonyl feedstocks under UV and sulfur-based reduction yields the C2 and C3 sugars needed for nucleotide assembly.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the central sugar-forming branch of the cyanosulfidic network: glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde are produced through HCN reductive homologation under UV/H2S chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"2-Aminooxazole formation from glycolaldehyde and cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"phosphate-buffered solution; >80% yield reported\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of a C2 sugar fragment with cyanamide gives the chimeric heterocycle 2-aminooxazole.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Powner\u2013Sutherland network begins with glycolaldehyde + cyanamide in phosphate buffer to form 2-aminooxazole in >80% yield; borate is included as a surface sugar-stabilizing mineral consistent with pentose chemistry in the report (Anastasi, Crowe, Powner & Sutherland, 2006; Powner, Gerland & Sutherland, 2009; Ricardo et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Pentose aminooxazoline formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate-buffered aqueous medium\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"essentially quantitative formation of pentose aminooxazolines; ribo and arabino stereoisomers\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"2-Aminooxazole condenses with glyceraldehyde to form pentose aminooxazolines, embedding sugar and base fragments in one intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is directly from the Sutherland pathway and solves the free-ribose/glycosidic bond problem by generating pentose aminooxazolines rather than free ribose and base (Anastasi et al., 2006; Powner, Gerland & Sutherland, 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene generation from HCN-derived chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"photochemical surface chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated flow setting; network representation of HCN/acetylene-derived cyanoacetylene supply\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical oxidative coupling in surface settings generates cyanoacetylene as a shared pyrimidine precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanoacetylene is identified in the report as a required intermediate for both classical pyrimidine synthesis and the Sutherland route; its production from HCN/acetylene chemistry follows the unified cyanosulfidic scenario (Patel et al., 2015; Sasselov, Grotzinger & Sutherland, 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Powner-Sutherland assembly of cytidine-2',3'-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate and urea-assisted phosphorylation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanoacetylene addition at pH 6.5 in phosphate buffer, followed by heating with inorganic phosphate in urea to stereoinvert to ribo cyclic phosphate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Arabino aminooxazoline reacts with cyanoacetylene to form an anhydrocytidine intermediate; subsequent phosphate/urea-mediated phosphorylation and intramolecular displacement yields \u03b2-ribo-cytidine-2',3'-cyclic phosphate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the principal literature-supported route to cytosine chemistry because it bypasses free cytosine and direct glycosylation entirely; phosphate is essential throughout as buffer, catalyst, nucleophile, and reactant (Powner, Gerland & Sutherland, 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Dephosphorylation or hydrolysis of cytidine cyclic phosphate to cytidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool or membrane-associated hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyclic phosphate opening/dephosphorylation yields cytidine as the immediate nucleoside precursor to free cytosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This connection is necessary to bridge the Sutherland nucleotide pathway to free cytosine as target. It is chemically straightforward although not the emphasized endpoint in Powner et al.; included as a conservative completion step because the user requested cytosine specifically and the report stresses cytidine/cytidine-cyclic-phosphate as the kinetically favored prebiotic species (Powner, Gerland & Sutherland, 2009; Shapiro, 1999).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of cytidine to cytosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild hydrolysis in prebiotic pools; rapid sequestration required because cytosine deaminates to uracil\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cleavage of the N-glycosidic bond from cytidine liberates free cytosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Used to translate nucleotide/nucleoside-centered routes into the requested target molecule. The reaction is chemically plausible but should be viewed as secondary to nucleotide accumulation because the report emphasizes that free cytosine is unstable and likely not the principal accumulated species (Levy & Miller, 1998; Wolfenden et al., 2016; Powner, Gerland & Sutherland, 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene plus cyanate to cyanovinylurea\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-concentrating surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"0.025 M cyanoacetylene and 0.05 M cyanate; 24 h\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetylene adds cyanate to form cyanovinylurea, the classical prebiotic pyrimidine precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel route, giving trans-cyanovinylurea as the immediate precursor to cytosine under heating; mineral surfaces are added only as environmentally plausible concentrators per schema requirements, while the core chemistry and conditions follow the literature (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1968).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyclization of cyanovinylurea to cytosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"alkaline aqueous cyclization on drying mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"classically 100C; isolated trans-cyanovinylurea converts to cytosine efficiently in alkali\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Intramolecular cyclization and rearrangement of cyanovinylurea generates the pyrimidin-2-one ring of cytosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly supported by the original classical cytosine synthesis literature, with up to 6% cytosine under the cited reaction and near-quantitative conversion from isolated trans-cyanovinylurea in strong base (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1968).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"303K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH about 9; hydrolysis half-life about 11 days at 30C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aqueous hydrolysis of cyanoacetylene converts the C3N alkyne to the more stable aldehydic nitrile cyanoacetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied report explicitly identifies cyanoacetaldehyde as the hydrolysis product of cyanoacetylene and notes its much greater stability, making it a major hub for direct cytosine synthesis (Robertson & Miller, 1995; Nelson et al., 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde plus urea condensation to cytosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"drying lagoon / evaporitic concentration on minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"100C; 5-120 molal urea gives about 20-53% yield; dry-down with 2 M urea and cyanoacetaldehyde dimer gives 12.8% in 3 days\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of cyanoacetaldehyde with concentrated urea closes the pyrimidine ring directly to cytosine under heating and drying.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the highest-yielding direct free-cytosine pathway in the supplied report and is a core alternative branch in the network (Robertson & Miller, 1995; Nelson, Robertson, Levy & Miller, 2001; Cleaves, Nelson & Miller, 2006).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde plus guanidine to 2,4-diaminopyrimidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"333-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"concentrating dry-down mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated drying-lagoon conditions; reported 40-85% yields of 2,4-diaminopyrimidine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde condenses with guanidine to produce the diaminated pyrimidine precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route exploits the exceptional hydrolytic stability of guanidine and is directly supported by the cited studies on 2,4-diaminopyrimidine formation from cyanoacetaldehyde (Ferris et al., 1974; Robertson, Levy & Miller, 1996).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of 2,4-diaminopyrimidine to cytosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous hydrolysis producing cytosine among products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial hydrolysis/deamination of the diaminopyrimidine converts one exocyclic amino functionality to the 2-oxo state of cytosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ferris and coworkers reported that 2,4-diaminopyrimidine hydrolyzes to cytosine, isocytosine, and uracil; this branch is therefore literature-supported but inherently selectivity-limited (Ferris et al., 1974).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN polymerization to DAMN under eutectic concentration\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_026\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_027\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"195-298K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"eutectic concentration on mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"0.1-0.15 M NH4CN, pH about 9.2, room temperature months or frozen storage; HCN-H2O eutectic concentration important\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise HCN oligomerization via iminoacetonitrile and aminomalononitrile gives diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied report identifies DAMN as the key branch-point tetramer from HCN oligomerization and notes that frozen eutectic concentration is the most plausible way to reach required concentrations (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1967; Miyakawa, Cleaves & Miller, 2002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of HCN polymers to trace cytosine-containing product pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_027\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"195-298K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"acid hydrolysis of frozen-derived polymer\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"trace cytosine after long-term NH4CN freezing and polymer hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex HCN polymer hydrolysis liberates a low-yield nucleobase mixture containing trace cytosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct HCN oligomerization is not an efficient cytosine route, but the report documents trace cytosine after 27-year frozen NH4CN storage followed by hydrolysis, so it must be represented as a minor pathway (Miyakawa, Cleaves & Miller, 2002; Ferris et al., 1977; Ferris et al., 1978).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of HCN to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-surface assisted hydrolysis/concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic concentration precursor to neat formamide chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis and concentration of HCN yield formamide, a one-carbon feedstock for nucleobase synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly identifies formamide as the HCN hydrolysis product and the basis for multiple nucleobase syntheses (Saladino et al., 2001; Saladino et al., 2003; Saladino et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal condensation of formamide to cytosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"1-2% w/w mineral catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"160C for 48 h in neat formamide\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thermally driven condensation and cyclization of formamide on mineral catalysts forms nucleobases including cytosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Saladino and coworkers demonstrated cytosine formation from neat formamide at 160C for 48 h with mineral catalysts; montmorillonite specifically gives uracil and cytosine among products (Saladino et al., 2001; Saladino et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photochemistry of formamide on TiO2 to cytosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2(001) photocatalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation of adsorbed formamide\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoexcited TiO2 promotes formamide fragmentation, recombination, and heterocycle formation, releasing nucleobases including cytosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"UV-driven conversion of formamide on TiO2 surfaces to all five nucleobases was demonstrated by Senanayake and Idriss, and TiO2 is a required surface mineral class in the schema (Senanayake & Idriss, 2006; Saladino et al., 2003).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"DAP-mediated phosphorylation of cytidine to cytidine cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous phosphorylation; pyrimidine ribonucleosides efficiently give 2',3'-cyclic phosphates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Diamidophosphate transfers phosphate to the vicinal diol of cytidine, yielding the activated 2',3'-cyclic phosphate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"DAP is highlighted in the report as the leading geochemically plausible phosphorylating agent, especially effective for pyrimidine nucleosides to form 2',3'-cyclic phosphates; this provides an alternative convergence to the same nucleotide hub (Gibard et al., 2018; Casta\u00f1eda et al., 2019; Pasek & Krishnamurthy, 2025).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Primary Sutherland nucleotide-first route\",\n      \"description\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic pathway from hydrothermal carbon feedstocks through glycolaldehyde, 2-aminooxazole, pentose aminooxazoline, and cytidine cyclic phosphate, ending in cytosine via cytidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde-urea direct synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN-derived cyanoacetylene hydrolyzes to cyanoacetaldehyde, which condenses with concentrated urea in drying pools to give cytosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical cyanoacetylene-cyanate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetylene reacts with cyanate to cyanovinylurea, which cyclizes to cytosine under heating.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde-guanidine branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde condenses with guanidine to 2,4-diaminopyrimidine, which hydrolyzes to cytosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Frozen HCN oligomerization branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Eutectically concentrated ammonium cyanide oligomerizes to DAMN-containing polymers that yield trace cytosine after hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_027\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide thermal mineral route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN hydrolyzes to formamide, which thermally condenses on mineral catalysts to cytosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide UV-TiO2 route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN-derived formamide undergoes UV photochemistry on TiO2 surfaces to give cytosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_019\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-cyanoacetaldehyde surface route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation supplies formaldehyde, which links into HCN-rich surface chemistry producing cyanoacetylene and then cyanoacetaldehyde for the urea pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"DAP-supported cytidine activation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cytidine produced from the Sutherland branch is re-activated by DAP to the cyclic phosphate hub before release of cytosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent cyanoacetylene hub route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetylene acts as a convergence point feeding both the classical cyanate pathway and the more stable cyanoacetaldehyde route to cytosine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_020\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_022\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Cytosine", "overall_strategy": "The network prioritizes literature-supported surface cyanosulfidic and cyanoacetaldehyde chemistry while using hydrothermal iron-sulfur chemistry to supply shared C1/C2 feedstocks (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, pyruvate) and biochemical stages to convert assembled pyrimidine nucleotides or nucleosides into free cytosine where relevant. Because free cytosine is hydrolytically unstable, the primary route follows the Powner\u2013Sutherland strategy in which the pyrimidine ring is built on a sugar-phosphate scaffold and cytosine is accessed through cytidine/cytidine-cyclic-phosphate intermediates. Alternative literature-supported branches include cyanoacetaldehyde + urea, cyanoacetylene + cyanate, cyanoacetaldehyde + guanidine, formamide thermolysis on minerals, UV formamide photochemistry on TiO2, frozen NH4CN oligomerization, and meteoritic/interstellar delivery analogs. Hub molecules are HCN, cyanoacetylene, cyanoacetaldehyde, 2-aminooxazole, and cytidine-2',3'-cyclic phosphate.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "fo