gression\": 0.75,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.94,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway aligns well with the Robertson-Miller literature and is one of the strongest branches in the network. Hydrolysis of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde is well supported, and condensation of cyanoacetaldehyde with concentrated urea at about 100 C is the highest-yielding direct free-cytosine route reported. The main weakness is upstream supply: deriving cyanoacetylene solely from generic HCN chemistry is underspecified and not well represented mechanistically. Also, successful cytosine synthesis here requires highly concentrated urea or drying/freezing concentration, which is not explicit in the path definition. Nevertheless, the core chemistry is sound and target achievement is strong.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Specify concentrated urea/dry-down or eutectic freezing conditions for rxn_014.\",\n        \"Provide a more plausible prebiotic source for cyanoacetylene, such as atmospheric discharge chemistry or acetylene/HCN coupling, rather than a one-step HCN conversion.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.41,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.94\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.77,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.76,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.93,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n      \"feedback\": \"This branch is strongly literature-aligned for the classical Sanchez-Ferris-Orgel route. The cyanoacetylene + cyanate -> trans-cyanovinylurea step and cyclization to cytosine are both well established experimentally and are represented coherently. The main issue is again the poor upstream generation of cyanoacetylene. The pathway also should note the demanding concentration requirements and instability of both cyanoacetylene and cyanate in water. Despite that, the direct route to cytosine is chemically valid.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add explicit high-cyanate concentration and heating conditions near 100 C for the classical synthesis.\",\n        \"Note that isolated cyanovinylurea cyclizes best under alkaline conditions; include that detail in the reaction conditions.\",\n        \"Improve the prebiotic sourcing of cyanoacetylene.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.41,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.71\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.75,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.76,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n      \"feedback\": \"The cyanoacetaldehyde + guanidine branch is literature-supported up to 2,4-diaminopyrimidine formation and fits known concentrated drying-lagoon chemistry. The weak point is the last conversion: hydrolysis of 2,4-diaminopyrimidine gives mixtures including cytosine, isocytosine, and uracil, so representing it as a clean cytosine-forming step overstates selectivity. Upstream cyanoacetylene sourcing remains underspecified.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_007\",\n        \"rxn_016\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Represent rxn_016 as producing a mixed pyrimidine product pool rather than only cytosine.\",\n        \"Include concentration/dry-down conditions for the guanidine condensation.\",\n        \"Improve upstream cyanoacetylene formation chemistry.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.89,\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.18\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\